1. What are the Pillars of OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)?
The 4 Pillars of OOP:
Encapsulation isÂ  to the bundling of data and methods that operate on that data within a single unit, which is called a class in Java. Java Encapsulation is a way of hiding the implementation details of a class from outside access and only exposing a public interface that can be used to interact with the class.
Â 
inheritance we use to reuse all the property of parent in our child you can go with class and interface in the same type if it is a class class or interface interface you can go with extends if the type is different you can go with implements the next polymorphism
Â 
poly means single with multiple implementation okay which is nothing our overloading and overridingÂ 
Method Overloadingâ€‚is aÂ Compile time polymorphism. In method overloading, more than one method shares the same method name with a different signature in the class. In method overloading, the return type can or can not be the same, but we have to change the parameter because, in java, we can not achieve method overloading by changing only the return type of the method.Â 
Â 
Method Overriding is a type of runtime polymorphism. In method overriding, Method overriding is used to grant the specific implementation of the method which is already provided by its parent class or superclass.
Â 
// Overloading
void greet() {}
void greet(String name) {}
Â 
// Overriding
class Animal {
Â Â Â Â void sound() {}
}
class Dog extends Animal {
Â Â Â Â @Override
Â Â Â Â void sound() {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â System.out.println("Bark");
Â Â Â Â }
}
Â 
Â 
Abstraction is means hiding implementationÂ  and showing functionality
Real-world Example (Encapsulation):
public class BankAccount {
Â Â Â Â private double balance; // Encapsulated field
Â 
Â Â Â Â public void deposit(double amount) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â balance += amount;
Â Â Â Â }
