Hereâ€™s a simple explanationÂ of the types of memory in Java:



ï¿½ï¿½ 1. Heap Memory
Â·Â 
Used for: Objects and instance variables
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Allocated at runtime using newÂ keyword.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Managed by Garbage CollectorÂ (frees memory automatically).
Â·Â 
Student s = new Student(); // Stored in heap
âœ… Big memory area, shared among all threads.



ï¿½ï¿½ 2. Stack Memory
Â·Â 
Used for: Method calls, local variables
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Follows LIFOÂ (Last-In-First-Out).
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Each thread has its own stack.
Â·Â 
void greet() {
Â Â Â Â int x = 10; // x is stored in stack
}
âœ… Fast but limited in size.



ï¿½ï¿½ 3. Method Area (MetaSpace in Java 8+)
Â·Â 
Stores: Class-level data, like:
Â·Â 
oÂ 
Class definitions
oÂ 
oÂ 
Static variables
oÂ 
oÂ 
Method code (bytecode)
oÂ 
âœ… Shared among all classes.



ï¿½ï¿½ 4. Program Counter (PC) Register
Â·Â 
Each thread has its own PC register.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Keeps track of the current instructionÂ being executed.
Â·Â 
âœ… Small memory block, used internally by JVM.



ï¿½ï¿½ 5. Native Method Stack
Â·Â 
Used when Java code calls native (C/C++) codeÂ using JNI (Java Native Interface).
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Stores native method information.
Â·Â 



âœ… Summary Table:
Memory Type	Stores	Scope
Heap	Objects, instance variables	Shared
Stack	Local variables, method calls	Per thread
Method Area	Class info, static variables, bytecode	Shared
PC Register	Current executing instruction	Per thread
Native Method Stack	Native code info	Per thread


Let me know if you want a diagramÂ or interview-focused Q&AÂ on this topic!



âœ… 1. Single Inheritance
Â·Â 
One class inherits from another.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Only one parent and one child.
Â·Â 
class Animal {
Â Â Â Â void sound() { System.out.println("Animal sound"); }
}
Â 
class Dog extends Animal {
Â Â Â Â void bark() { System.out.println("Dog barks"); }
}
âœ… DogÂ gets properties of Animal.



âœ… 2. Multilevel Inheritance
Â·Â 
A class inherits from a class which itself inherits another class.
Â·Â 
class Animal {
Â Â Â Â void eat() { System.out.println("Animal eats"); }
}
Â 
class Dog extends Animal {
Â Â Â Â void bark() { System.out.println("Dog barks"); }
}
Â 
class Puppy extends Dog {
Â Â Â Â void weep() { System.out.println("Puppy weeps"); }
}
âœ… PuppyÂ â†’ inherits from DogÂ â†’ inherits from Animal.



âœ… 3. Hierarchical Inheritance
Â·Â 
Multiple classes inherit from one base class.
Â·Â 
class Animal {
Â Â Â Â void eat() { System.out.println("Animal eats"); }
}
Â 
class Dog extends Animal {
Â Â Â Â void bark() { System.out.println("Dog barks"); }
}
Â 
class Cat extends Animal {
Â Â Â Â void meow() { System.out.println("Cat meows"); }
}
âœ… Both DogÂ and CatÂ inherit from Animal.



ï¿½ï¿½ 4. Multiple Inheritance (Not supported with classes)
Â·Â 
Java does not allowÂ a class to inherit from more than one classÂ (to avoid confusion called "Diamond Problem").
Â·Â 
// âŒ This will cause error
class A { }
class B { }
class C extends A, B { } // Not allowed



âœ… 5. Multiple Inheritance with Interfaces (Supported)
Â·Â 
Java allows multiple inheritance through interfaces.
Â·Â 
interface A {
Â Â Â Â void show();
}
Â 
interface B {
Â Â Â Â void display();
}
Â 
class C implements A, B {
Â Â Â Â public void show() { System.out.println("A's method"); }
Â Â Â Â public void display() { System.out.println("B's method"); }
}
âœ… Class CÂ implements both AÂ and BÂ interfaces.



âœ… Summary Table:
Type	Supported?	Example
Single Inheritance	âœ… Yes	One class â†’ another
Multilevel Inheritance	âœ… Yes	A â†’ B â†’ C
Hierarchical	âœ… Yes	A â†’ B and A â†’ C
Multiple (classes)	âŒ No	A, B â†’ C (Not allowed)
Multiple (interfaces)	âœ… Yes	Interface A, B â†’ Class C implements


