1. What Is an Exception and Its Hierarchy?
ï¿½ï¿½ Exception:Â An unwanted or unexpected event that disrupts the normal flow of a program.
ï¿½ï¿½ Exception Hierarchy:
Object Â 
Â â””â”€â”€ Throwable Â 
Â Â Â Â Â Â â”œâ”€â”€ Error Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â (e.g., OutOfMemoryError)
Â Â Â Â Â Â â””â”€â”€ Exception Â 
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â â”œâ”€â”€ RuntimeException (unchecked) Â 
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â â””â”€â”€ IOException, SQLException, etc. (checked)
Type	Description
Checked Exception	Known at compile-time (e.g., IOException)
Unchecked Exception	Known at runtime (e.g., NullPointerException)
Error	Serious issues like OutOfMemoryError

ï¿¼
ï¿½ï¿½ Interview Tip:Â Unchecked = RuntimeExceptionÂ & its subclasses.



2. How to Write a Custom Exception?
âœ… Use when built-in exceptions aren't enough.

class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
Â Â Â Â public InvalidAgeException(String message) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â super(message);
Â Â Â Â }
}
Â 
public class Test {
