8. What is a Functional Interface?
A Functional Interface in Java is an interface that has only one abstract method.
â¡ï¸ It can have default or static methods, but only one abstract method.

ğŸ”¹ Why Are They Important?
They are used to implement lambda expressions and method references, introduced in Java 8.
ğŸ’¡ Java provides many built-in functional interfaces in java.util.function package like Predicate, Function, Consumer, etc.

ğŸ§  Real-Life Analogy:
Think of a functional interface like a contract with one responsibility â€” like a remote with only one button that does one specific thing.

âœ… How to Create a Functional Interface?
Use the @FunctionalInterface annotation (optional but recommended for compile-time checking).

ğŸ‘‡ Code Example:
@FunctionalInterface
interface Greet {
    void sayHello(String name);
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Using Lambda Expression
        Greet greeting = (name) -> System.out.println("Hello, " + name);
        greeting.sayHello("Roy");  // Output: Hello, Roy
    }
}

ğŸ§  Key Points for Interview:
Feature	Details
Only One Abstract Method	Must (required for lambda support)
Can Have Default Methods	âœ… Yes
Can Have Static Methods	âœ… Yes
Used With	Lambda expressions, method references
Annotation (@FunctionalInterface)	Optional, but helps avoid errors

ğŸ—£ Interview Summary Line:
â€œA functional interface has exactly one abstract method, making it ideal for lambda expressions. It's a key part of functional programming in Java 8.â€

Â·Â 



9. Java Stream Operations: filter, map, reduce
These are core stream operations used for processing collections in a functional way.

ğŸ”¹ 1. filter()
Used to select elements that match a condition.
ğŸ”¸ Think: "Keep only those elements that pass a test."
âœ… Example:
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6);

// Filter even numbers
List<Integer> evens = numbers.stream()
                             .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
                             .collect(Collectors.toList());

System.out.println(evens);  // Output: [2, 4, 6]

ğŸ”¹ 2. map()
Used to transform elements.
ğŸ”¸ Think: "Convert each element into something else."
âœ… Example:
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Roy", "Robert", "Java");

// Convert each name to uppercase
List<String> upperNames = names.stream()
                               .map(String::toUpperCase)
                               .collect(Collectors.toList());

System.out.println(upperNames);  // Output: [ROY, ROBERT, JAVA]

ğŸ”¹ 3. reduce()
Used to combine all elements into a single result.
ğŸ”¸ Think: "Reduce a list into one value (sum, product, etc.)."
âœ… Example:
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4);

// Sum of all numbers
int sum = numbers.stream()
                 .reduce(0, (a, b) -> a + b);

System.out.println(sum);  // Output: 10

ğŸ§  Interview Summary:
"filter() selects elements, map() transforms them, and reduce() combines them into one result. These are powerful tools for processing collections using Java Streams."

ğŸ”„ Visual Flow:
Original List -> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]

filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)  â†’ [2, 4, 6]
map(n -> n * 10)         â†’ [20, 40, 60]
reduce(0, sum)           â†’ 120



