4. Why Set doesnâ€™t allow duplicates?
Sets use equals()Â and hashCode()Â to check for uniqueness. If two objects return trueÂ for equals(), only one is retained.



5. Difference between Comparable and Comparator
Comparable	Comparator
1) Comparable provides aÂ single sorting sequence. In other words, we can sort the collection on the basis of a single element such as id, name, and price.	The Comparator providesÂ multiple sorting sequences. In other words, we can sort the collection on the basis of multiple elements such as id, name, and price etc.
2) ComparableÂ affects the original class, i.e., the actual class is modified.	ComparatorÂ doesn't affect the original class, i.e., the actual class is not modified.
3) Comparable providesÂ compareTo() methodÂ to sort elements.	Comparator providesÂ compare() methodÂ to sort elements.
4) Comparable is present inÂ java.langÂ package.	A Comparator is present in theÂ java.utilÂ package.
5) We can sort the list elements of Comparable type byÂ Collections.sort(List)Â method.	We can sort the list elements of Comparator type byÂ Collections.sort(List, Comparator)Â method.



6. Fail-Fast vs Fail-Safe Iterator
A iterator which will fail fast when we do any modifications while iterating a collection is called fail fast iterator ex: array list , hashmap, and vector (ConcurrentmodificationExcpetion)

Iterator who allow us to modify in middle while iterating a collection is called non fail fast iterator ex: copyonwritearraylist , copy on write array set , concurrent hashmap

Feature	Fail-Fast	Fail-Safe
Throws Exception	Yes (ConcurrentModificationException)	No
Examples	ArrayList, HashMap	CopyOnWriteArrayList, ConcurrentHashMap


7. Why use ConcurrentHashMap?
Â·Â 
Allows concurrent reads and writes.

Uses internal segmentation or lock stripping.

Safer and faster than synchronizing a HashMap.


âœ… What is ConcurrentHashMap in Java?
ConcurrentHashMap is a thread-safe variant of HashMap designed for high concurrency.

ğŸ”¹ Key Points:
* Allows multiple threads to read and write without blocking each other unnecessarily.
* Uses fine-grained locking (called lock striping) instead of locking the entire map.
* Improves performance in multi-threaded environments compared to synchronized HashMap or Hashtable.
* Doesnâ€™t allow null keys or values.

8. Internal Working of HashMap & HashSet
Â·Â 
HashMap:Â Uses array of buckets; keys are hashed to determine bucket index. Handles collisions using linked list or tree (Java 8+)
HashSet:Â Backed by HashMapÂ internally. Elements are stored as keys.

Hereâ€™s a clear and simple explanation of the internal working of HashMap and HashSet in Java, including memory structures, method flow, and collision handling.

ğŸ”¹ 1. Internal Working of HashMap<K, V>
A HashMap stores key-value pairs and is based on the concept of hashing for fast access.
ğŸ”¸ Step-by-Step How put(key, value) Works:
1. hashCode() is called on the key.
2. HashMap computes an index using:â€¨index = (n - 1) & hash   // where n is the capacity of the array
3. 
4. It checks the bucket (array slot) at that index:
    * If empty, inserts a new Node<K,V>.
    * If not empty (collision):
        * Uses equals() to check if key already exists.
        * If yes, it updates the value.
        * If not, adds the new node to the end (as a LinkedList or Tree).
5. In Java 8+, if there are more than 8 entries in one bucket and the array size is â‰¥ 64, the LinkedList is converted to a Red-Black Tree for faster lookup.
ğŸ”¸ How get(key) Works:
1. Calculate hashCode() and find index.
2. Go to that bucket:
    * If one node â†’ return value.
    * If multiple (chained list or tree) â†’ use equals() to find correct key.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Internal Working of HashSet
A HashSet uses HashMap<E, Object> internally to store elements.
ğŸ”¸ Key Concept:
private transient HashMap<E, Object> map;
private static final Object PRESENT = new Object();
When you call:
set.add("apple");
It actually does:
map.put("apple", PRESENT);
So, it inherits all behaviors of HashMap â€” hashing, collisions, etc.

ğŸ”¸ Why No Duplicates in HashSet?
Because HashMap does not allow duplicate keys â€” so when put() is called with an existing key, it replaces the value (no duplicate is added).

âœ… Summary Comparison:
Feature	HashMap<K, V>	HashSet<E>
Purpose	Stores key-value pairs	Stores unique values only
Underlying DS	Array + LinkedList / Tree	Uses HashMap<E, Object>
Collision Handling	LinkedList / Tree (Java 8+)	Same as HashMap
Null Allowed	One null key, many null values	One null element
Duplicate Check	Based on keyâ€™s equals() and hashCode()	Based on elementâ€™s equals() and hashCode()
ğŸ” Real-World Analogy:
* HashMap â†’ A locker room with labeled lockers (keys). You can store a name tag and item inside (key + value).
* HashSet â†’ Just the labels on lockers (you donâ€™t care about the item inside â€” dummy object).

9. Difference between HashMap and TreeMap
Feature	HashMap	TreeMap
Ordering	No order	Sorted by key (natural or comparator)
Null Keys	One allowed	Not allowed
Performance	Faster	Slower (Red-Black tree)

Here's a simple and clear explanation of the difference between HashMap and TreeMap in Java:

âœ… HashMap vs TreeMap â€” Side-by-Side Comparison
Feature	HashMap	TreeMap
Ordering	âŒ No order (random or hash-based)	âœ… Sorted by keys (natural or custom order)
Underlying Structure	Hash Table (Buckets + LinkedList/Tree)	Red-Black Tree (Self-balancing BST)
Performance	âœ… Faster (O(1) average for get/put)	âŒ Slower (O(log n) for get/put)
Allows null key?	âœ… Yes (only one null key allowed)	âŒ No (NullPointerException if key is null)
Thread-safe?	âŒ No (use Collections.synchronizedMap)	âŒ No (same here)
Use Case	When speed matters, no need for order	When sorted keys are required
Implements	Map, Cloneable, Serializable	NavigableMap, SortedMap, Map
ğŸ”¹ Code Example: HashMap
Map<String, Integer> hashMap = new HashMap<>();
hashMap.put("Banana", 20);
hashMap.put("Apple", 10);
hashMap.put("Cherry", 30);

System.out.println(hashMap);
// Output may be random: {Banana=20, Cherry=30, Apple=10}

ğŸ”¹ Code Example: TreeMap
Map<String, Integer> treeMap = new TreeMap<>();
treeMap.put("Banana", 20);
treeMap.put("Apple", 10);
treeMap.put("Cherry", 30);

System.out.println(treeMap);
// Output sorted by key: {Apple=10, Banana=20, Cherry=30}

âœ… When to Use What?
* ğŸŸ¢ Use HashMap:
    * When you need fast lookup, insertion, and deletion
    * Key ordering doesn't matter
* ğŸŸ¢ Use TreeMap:
    * When you need keys sorted automatically
    * When working with range queries, like sub-maps or head/tail maps

