## 2. What is the difference between execution in Executor Framework?
Â 
| Method Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â | Description Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â | Return Type |
|-----------------|------------------------------------------------------|-------------|
| `execute(Runnable)` | Submits a task for execution, no result returned. | void Â Â Â Â Â Â Â |
| `submit(Runnable/Callable)` | Submits a task and returns a `Future` representing the result or status. | Future<?> |
Â 
**Example:**
Â 
```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
Â 
executor.execute(() -> System.out.println("Run task"));
Â 
Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(() -> {
Â Â Â Â Thread.sleep(1000);
Â Â Â Â return 123;
});
Integer result = future.get(); Â // Blocks until done



3. What is a BlockingQueue?
Â·Â 
A thread-safe queue that blocks producer threads when full and consumer threads when empty.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Used for producer-consumer patterns.
Â·Â 
Common Implementations:
Â·Â 
ArrayBlockingQueue
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
LinkedBlockingQueue
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
PriorityBlockingQueue
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
SynchronousQueueÂ (special case with zero capacity)
Â·Â 
Example:
BlockingQueue<String> queue = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(10);
queue.put("item"); Â Â Â Â Â Â // Blocks if full
String item = queue.take(); // Blocks if empty



4. How do we know thread pool is exhausted or has empty thread?
Â·Â 
Use ThreadPoolExecutorÂ methods:
Â·Â 
oÂ 
getActiveCount()Â returns number of threads currently executing tasks
oÂ 
oÂ 
getPoolSize()Â returns current number of threads in the pool
oÂ 
Â·Â 
When active count equals max pool size, the pool is exhausted.
Â·Â 
ThreadPoolExecutor executor = (ThreadPoolExecutor) Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);
int active = executor.getActiveCount();
int max = executor.getMaximumPoolSize();
Â 
if (active == max) {
Â Â Â Â System.out.println("Thread pool exhausted");
}

